# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: windows-registry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] A **configuration file**, also known as **config file**, is a file that stores data used to configure a software system such as an application, a server or an operating system.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Some applications provide a tool to create, modify, and verify the syntax of their configuration files – sometimes via graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] For context, system administrators may be expected to create and modify text config files via a text editor.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] For server processes and operating-system settings, there is often no standard tool, but operating systems may provide graphical interfaces such as YaST or debconf.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Some computer programs only read their configuration files at startup.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Others periodically check the configuration files for changes.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Users can instruct some programs to re-read the configuration files and apply the changes to the current process, or indeed to read arbitrary files as a configuration file.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] There are no definitive standards or strong conventions.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] In general, a config file can have any format.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] The format that applies to a particular system is determined by the design of that system.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Often, a standardized format is used since it allows for using tools designed for the format even if not designed for the consuming system.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] In particular, general-purpose serialization formats, such as JSON, XML, and YAML, are often used in open-source and platform-neutral software.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] The specifications for these formats are generally publicly available to support wide-spread use.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] The following table compares notable formats used for configuration data.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] The *syntax typing* column indicates whether the syntax supports data types.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] A format has syntax-typing if a value's type is specified by syntax – e.g.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] `true` is a Boolean while `"true"` is a string.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] A format does not have syntax-typing if a value's type is based on semantics – e.g.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] `true` and `"true"` are both Boolean if the parser expects a Boolean.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Opinions on the value of syntax-typing vary.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] The following are examples of config files organized by the operating systems on which they are commonly used.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Many different file formats are used on Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Even so, there is a strong tradition of using human-editable, plain text formats including simple key–value pair.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Filename extensions of `.cnf`, `.conf`, `.cfg`, `.cf` or `.ini` are often used.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Many formats allow comments, in which case, individual settings can be disabled by prepending with the comment character.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Often the default configuration files contain extensive internal documentation in the form of comments and man files are also typically used to document the format and options available.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] System-wide software often uses configuration files stored in `/etc`, while user applications often use a "dotfile" – a file or directory in the home directory prefixed with a period, which in Unix hides the file or directory from casual listing.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Since this causes pollution, newer user applications generally make their own folder in the `.config` directory, a standardized subdirectory of the home directory.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Similar to config files, a run command (rc) shell script can configure a shell session.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Often, such scripts are named with an `rc` suffix after the consuming program's name such as `.xinitrc`, `.vimrc`, `.bashrc`, `xsane.rc`.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] By contrast, IBM's AIX uses an Object Data Manager (ODM) database to store much of its system settings.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] MS-DOS primarily relied on the `CONFIG.SYS` config file, a plain text file with simple key–value pairs (e.g.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] MS-DOS 6 introduced the INI-file format.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Similar to an rc file, the batch file named `AUTOEXEC.BAT` ran commands on startup.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Both these files were retained up to Windows 98SE, which still ran on top of MS-DOS.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] DOS applications used a wide variety of individual configuration files, most of them binary, proprietary and undocumented - and there were no common conventions or formats.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Early Windows operating systems heavily utilized plain-text INI files which served as the primary mechanism to configure the operating system and applications.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] The APIs to read and write from these still exist in Windows, but after 1993, Microsoft began to steer developers away from using INI files and toward storing settings in the registry, a hierarchical database to store configuration settings, which was introduced with Windows NT.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Later systems use XML and other formats instead of the registry.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] The Property List is the standard configuration file format in macOS (as well as in iOS, NeXTSTEP, GNUstep and Cocoa applications).
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] It uses the filename extension `.plist`.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] IBM's OS/2 uses a binary format, also with a .INI suffix, but this differs from the Windows versions.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] It contains a list of lists of untyped key–value pairs.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Two files control system-wide settings: OS2.INI and OS2SYS.INI.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] Application developers can choose whether to use them or to create a specific file for their applications.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] HarmonyOS and OpenHarmony-based operating systems use JSON config files, named `config.json`.
[src:windows-registry/configuration-file] The platform IDE, DevEco Studio, provides methods for editing `config.json`.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Active Directory servers disseminate group policies by listing them in their LDAP directory under objects of class `groupPolicyContainer`.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] These refer to fileserver paths (attribute `gPCFileSysPath`) that store the actual group policy objects, typically in an SMB share \\*domain.com*\SYSVOL shared by the Active Directory server.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] If a group policy has registry settings, the associated file share will have a file `registry.pol` with the registry settings that the client needs to apply.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] The Policy Editor (`gpedit.msc`) is not provided on Home (& Starter) editions of Windows.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Group Policies, in part, control what users can and cannot do on a computer system.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] For example, a Group Policy can be used to enforce a password complexity policy that prevents users from choosing an overly simple password.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Other examples include: allowing or preventing unidentified users from remote computers to connect to a network share, or to block/restrict access to certain folders.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] A set of such configurations is called a Group Policy Object (GPO).
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] As part of Microsoft's *IntelliMirror* technologies, Group Policy aims to reduce the cost of supporting users.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] IntelliMirror technologies relate to the management of disconnected machines or roaming users and include *roaming user profiles*, *folder redirection*, and *offline files*.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] To accomplish the goal of central management of a group of computers, machines should receive and enforce GPOs.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] A GPO that resides on a single machine only applies to that computer.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] To apply a GPO to a group of computers, Group Policy relies on Active Directory (or on third-party products like ZENworks Desktop Management) for distribution.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Active Directory can distribute GPOs to computers which belong to a Windows domain.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] By default, Microsoft Windows refreshes its policy settings every 90 minutes with a random 30 minutes offset.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] On domain controllers, Microsoft Windows does so every five minutes.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] During the refresh, it discovers, fetches and applies all GPOs that apply to the machine and to logged-on users.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Some settings - such as those for automated software installation, drive mappings, startup scripts or logon scripts - only apply during startup or user logon.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Since Windows XP, users can manually initiate a refresh of the group policy by using the `gpupdate` command from a command prompt.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] **Site** - Any Group Policies associated with the *Active Directory site* in which the computer resides.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] (An Active Directory site is a logical grouping of computers, intended to facilitate management of those computers based on their physical proximity.) If multiple policies are linked to a site, they are processed in the order set by the administrator.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] **Domain** - Any Group Policies associated with the Windows domain in which the computer resides.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] If multiple policies are linked to a domain, they are processed in the order set by the administrator.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] **Organizational Unit** - Group policies assigned to the *Active Directory organizational unit (OU)* in which the computer or user are placed.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] (OUs are logical units that help organizing and managing a group of users, computers or other Active Directory objects.) If multiple policies are linked to an OU, they are processed in the order set by the administrator.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] The resulting Group Policy settings applied to a given computer or user are known as the Resultant Set of Policy (RSoP).
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] RSoP information may be displayed for both computers and users using the `gpresult` command.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] A policy setting inside a hierarchical structure is ordinarily passed from parent to children, and from children to grandchildren, and so forth.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] It can be blocked or enforced to control what policies are applied at each level.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] If a higher level administrator (enterprise administrator) creates a policy that has inheritance blocked by a lower level administrator (domain administrator), this policy will still be processed.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Where a Group Policy Preference Settings is configured and there is also an equivalent Group Policy Setting configured, then the value of the Group Policy Setting will take precedence.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] The *System Policy Editor* was first introduced in Windows NT 4.0 Server.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Later, Windows 2000 Professional and Windows 2000 Server introduced *Group Policy Editor* based on Microsoft Management Console.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Group Policy Preferences are a way for the administrator to set policies that are not mandatory, but optional for the user or computer.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] There is a set of group policy setting extensions that were previously known as PolicyMaker.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Microsoft bought PolicyMaker and then integrated them with Windows Server 2008.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Microsoft has since released a migration tool that allows users to migrate PolicyMaker items to Group Policy Preferences.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Group Policy Preferences adds a number of new configuration items.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] These items also have a number of additional targeting options that can be used to granularly control the application of these setting items.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Group Policy Preferences are compatible with x86 and x64 versions of Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, and Windows Vista with the addition of the Client Side Extensions (also known as CSE).
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Client Side Extensions are now included in Windows Server 2008, Windows 7, and Windows Server 2008 R2.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Originally, Group Policies were modified using the Group Policy Edit tool that was integrated with Active Directory Users and Computers Microsoft Management Console (MMC) snap-in, but it was later split into a separate MMC snap-in called the Group Policy Management Console (GPMC).
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] The GPMC is now a user component in Windows Server 2008 and Windows Server 2008 R2 and is provided as a download as part of the Remote Server Administration Tools for Windows Vista and Windows 7.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Microsoft has also released a tool to make changes to Group Policy called Advanced Group Policy Management (a.k.a.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] This tool is available for any organization that has licensed the Microsoft Desktop Optimization Pack (a.k.a.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] This advanced tool allows administrators to have a check in/out process for modification Group Policy Objects, track changes to Group Policy Objects, and implement approval workflows for changes to Group Policy Objects.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] AGPM consists of two parts - server and client.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] The server is a Windows Service that stores its Group Policy Objects in an archive located on the same computer or a network share.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] The client is a snap-in to the Group Policy Management Console, and connects to the AGPM server.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Configuration of the client is performed via Group Policy.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Administrative Templates are a feature of Group Policy, a Microsoft technology for centralized management of machines and users in an Active Directory environment.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Administrative Templates facilitate the management of registry-based policy.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] An ADM file is used to describe both the user interface presented to the Group Policy administrator and the registry keys that should be updated on the target machines.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] An ADM file is a text file with a specific syntax which describes both the interface and the registry values which will be changed if the policy is enabled or disabled.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] ADM files are consumed by the Group Policy Object Editor (GPEdit).
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Windows XP Service Pack 2 shipped with five ADM files (system.adm, inetres.adm, wmplayer.adm, conf.adm and wuau.adm).
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] These are merged into a unified "namespace" in GPEdit and presented to the administrator under the Administrative Templates node (for both machine and user policy).
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] View Filtering must be turned off in order to see custom preference settings (such as this example) in the Group Policy Editor.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] ADM files shipped with Microsoft operating systems include descriptions of policy settings for not just that platform but for all other platforms on which Group Policy is supported.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] For example, the Windows XP Service Pack 2 ADM files described policy settings not just for this platform but also for Windows 2000 and Windows Server 2003.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] This approach allows management of machines that are running an operating system other than that on which GPEdit is used.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] By default, ADM files are stored in each GPO, within Sysvol on domain controllers.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] This creates a simple and effective model for replicating ADM files across domain controllers (which is handled by the File Replication Service).
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] However, in some instances this can cause operational issues.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] To this end, various policy settings are available to manage the manner in which ADM files are read and stored.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] These are described in Microsoft's KB article 816662.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Starting with Windows Vista, ADM files have mostly been replaced with ADMX files (and their associated language-specific ADML files).
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] The ADMX file is structured in standard XML format, whereas the ADM files used a proprietary format.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Group Policy settings are enforced voluntarily by the targeted applications.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] In many cases, this merely consists of disabling the user interface for a particular function.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Alternatively, a malevolent user can modify or interfere with the application so that it cannot successfully read its Group Policy settings, thus enforcing potentially lower security defaults or even returning arbitrary values.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Group Policy was enhanced following its initial release in Windows 2000.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] For example, Windows XP has introduced a new feature called Group Policy Update which replaced the `secedit` command.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] This feature allows an administrator to force a group policy update on all computers with accounts in a particular Organizational Unit.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] This overrides the default scheduled task on the computer which runs the `gpupdate` command within 90 minutes, adjusted by a random offset to avoid overloading the domain controller.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Group Policy Infrastructure Status was introduced, which can report when any Group Policy Objects are not replicated correctly amongst domain controllers.
[src:windows-registry/group-policy] Group Policy Results Report also has a new feature that times the execution of individual components when doing a Group Policy Update.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] An **INI file** is a configuration file for computer software that consists of plain text with a structure and syntax comprising key–value pairs organized in sections.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The name of these configuration files comes from the filename extension *INI*, short for initialization, used in the MS-DOS operating system, which popularized this method of software configuration.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The format has become an informal standard in many contexts of configuration, but many applications on other operating systems use different filename extensions, such as *conf* and *cfg*.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The primary mechanism of software configuration in Windows was originally a text file format that comprised text lines with one key–value pair per line, organized into sections.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] This format was used for operating system components, such as device drivers, fonts, and startup launchers.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] INI files were also generally used by applications to store individual settings.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The format was maintained in 16-bit Microsoft Windows platforms up through Windows 3.1x.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Starting with Windows 95 Microsoft favored the use of the Windows Registry and began to steer developers away from using INI files for configuration.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] All subsequent versions of Windows have used the Windows Registry for system configuration, but applications built on the .NET Framework use special XML *.config* files.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The initialization-file functions are still available in Windows and developers may still use them.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Besides Windows software, platform-agnostic software may use this file format for configuration.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Some Unix-like config files also use a similar format.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] INI is human-readable and simple to parse, so it is a usable format for configuration files that do not require much greater complexity.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] What follows is a non-exhaustive list of places in which INI files appear.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The following example file has two sections: one for the owner of the software, and one for a payroll database connection.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Comments record the last person who modified the file and the reason for modification.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] In its broader sense, INI is an informal format which lends itself well to ad-hoc implementation while remaining human-configurable.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Consequently, many varying specifications (where sometimes a parser implementation is the only specification ever written) exist, called *INI dialects*.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] INI interpretations depend a lot on personal taste and the needs of the computing environment, such as whitespace preservation, field type information, case sensitivity, or preferred comment delimiters.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Nonetheless, *INI-flavoured* implementations typically share common design features: a text file consisting of a key–value pair on each line, delimited by an equals sign, organized into sections denoted by square brackets.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] In its most complicated interpretation, the INI format is able to express arbitrary S-expressions, making it equivalent to standardized formats like XML or JSON, albeit with a syntax which is not set in stone and to some may feel more comfortable.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] As the INI file format is not rigidly defined, many parsers support features beyond those that form the common core.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Attempts have been made to create parsers able to support as many dialects as possible.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Data in INI is held in key–value pairs called *key* or *property*.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] *Key* may thus either refer to the entire key–value pair or only its key.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] In its textual representation, the key–value pair is represented by either a line or a multiline where the start of the value is indicated by a delimiter, most often an equals sign (`=`, ASCII 0x3D) but sometimes also a colon (`:`, ASCII 0x3A) or whitespace (occasionally used in the GNU world).
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The key's key appears to the left of the delimiter, is often non-empty and should not contain the delimiter.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Some flavours allow escape sequences in the value.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] In the Windows implementation, the equals sign and the semicolon are reserved characters and cannot appear in the key.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Any whitespace surrounding the key is stripped by the parser.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The value can contain any character (in Windows-style, no whitespace surrounds the delimiter: e.g.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Key–value pairs may be grouped under a *section*.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Some INI dialects require every key–value pair to be in a section, some allow so-called *global properties*.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] When key–value pairs are grouped, the section name appears on a line by itself, enclosed in square brackets (`[`, ASCII 0x5B, and `]`, ASCII 0x5D), and applies to all key–value pairs on subsequent lines until another section is declared.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] There is no explicit "end of section" delimiter (such as e.g.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Thus, sections syntactically cannot be arbitrarily nested.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] When required, nesting can be implemented through flattening one's hierarchy and concatenating with a custom delimiter character inside the section name (often `.`, ASCII 0x2E).
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] One level of nesting is often supported, called *subsections*.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Some parsers did not offer nesting support at all and were hierarchy-blind, but nesting could still be partially emulated by exploiting the fact that `[A.B.C]` constitutes a unique identifier.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Section and property names in Windows are case insensitive.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Most Unix-style INI interpretations forbid case folding altogether, although case folding for the section name or key is sometimes allowed.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] A line with contiguous trailing whitespace followed by a semicolon (`;`, ASCII 0x3E) indicates a comment.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Some INI dialects furthermore allow use of the number sign (`#`, ASCII 0x23) to denote a comment, mirroring Unix shell comments.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Some INI dialects but not all allow a comment on a key–value pair line or section line (called *in-line comment*), where some require whitespace separating the value or section closing bracket from the comment.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The number sign might be nonetheless included in the key name in some dialects and ignored as such.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Comment lines are designed to be ignored by a parser.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Under the WinAPI's *GetPrivateProfileString*'s dialect, comments must occur on lines by themselves.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The order of properties in a section and the order of sections in a file is irrelevant.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Most implementations only support having one property with a given name in a section.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The second occurrence of a property name may cause an abort, it may be ignored (and the value discarded), or it may override the first occurrence (with the first value discarded).
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Some programs use duplicate property names to implement multi-valued properties.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Interpretation of multiple section declarations with the same name also varies.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] In some implementations, duplicate sections simply merge their properties, as if they occurred contiguously.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Others may abort or ignore some aspect of the INI file.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Some implementations allow values to be quoted, typically using double quotes and/or apostrophes.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] This allows for explicit declaration of whitespace, and/or for quoting of special characters (equals, semicolon, etc.).
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The standard Windows function GetPrivateProfileString supports this, and will remove quotation marks that surround the values.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Emulating C syntax, some dialects allow line folding by a backslash (`\`, ASCII 0x5C) as the last character on a line.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] In such *line continuation*, backslashes followed immediately by EOL (end-of-line) cause the backslash and line break to be dropped, transforming the document's lines into *logical lines*.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Some dialects offer varying support for character escaping, typically with the backslash character (`\`, ASCII 0x5C) as a metacharacter and emulating C syntax.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] It is not wise to blindly interpret escape sequences as some specifications explicitly mute their metacharacter for common escape sequences.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Under Windows, the *Profile API* is the programming interface used to read and write settings from classic Windows `.ini` files.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] For example, the GetPrivateProfileString function retrieves a string from the specified section in an initialization file.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The third parameter of the `GetPrivateProfileString` function is the default value, which are `"127.0.0.1"` and `143` respectively in the two function calls above.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] If the argument supplied for this parameter is `NULL`, the default is an empty string, `""`.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Under Unix, many different configuration libraries exist to access INI files.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] They are often already included in frameworks and toolkits.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Examples of INI parsers for Unix include GLib, iniparser and libconfini.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Initialization file mapping creates a mapping between an INI file and the Windows registry.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] It was introduced with Windows NT and Windows 95 as a way to migrate from storing settings in classic .ini files to the new registry.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] File mapping traps the Profile API calls and, using settings from the IniFileMapping Registry section, directs reads and writes to appropriate places in the Registry.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Using the example below, a string call could be made to fetch the *name* key from the *owner* section from a settings file called, say, dbsettings.ini.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] If this exists, it looks for an entry name matching the requested section.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] If an entry is found, INI mapping uses its value as a pointer to another part of the Registry.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] It then looks up the requested INI setting in that part of the Registry.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] If no matching entry name is found and there is an entry under the *(Default)* entry name, INI mapping uses that instead.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Thus each section name does not need its own entry.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] where the "*name*" Registry entry name is found to match the requested INI key.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The value of "John Doe" is then returned to the Profile call.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] In this case, the @ prefix on the default prevents any reads from going to the dbsettings.ini file on disk.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The result is that any settings not found in the Registry are not looked for in the INI file.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The "*database*" Registry entry does not have the @ prefix on the value; thus, for the `[database]` section *only*, settings in the Registry are taken first followed by settings in the dbsettings.ini file on disk.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Starting with Windows 95, Microsoft began strongly promoting the use of the Windows Registry over INI files.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] INI files are typically limited to two levels (sections and properties) and do not handle binary data well.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] This decision, however, has not been immune to critiques, due to the fact that the registry is monolithic, opaque, and binary, must be in sync with the filesystem, and represents a single point of failure for the operating system.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Later, XML-based configuration files became a popular choice for encoding configuration in text files.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] XML allows arbitrarily complex levels and nesting and has standard mechanisms for encoding binary data.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] More recently, data serialization formats, such as JSON, TOML, and YAML, can serve as configuration formats.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] These three alternative formats can nest arbitrarily but have a syntax different from INI.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] Among them, TOML most closely resembles INI, but the idea to make TOML deliberately compatible with a large subset of INI was rejected.
[src:windows-registry/ini-file] The newest INI parsers, however, also allow arbitrarily deep nesting like XML, JSON, TOML, and YAML, offer equivalent support of typed values and Unicode, although they keep the informal status of INI files by allowing multiple syntaxes for expressing the same thing.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The first version of Windows, Windows 1.0, was released on November 20, 1985 as a graphical operating system shell for MS-DOS in response to growing interest in graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The name *Windows* is a reference to the windowing system in GUIs.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The 1990 release of Windows 3.0 catapulted its market success and led to the launch of various other product families, including the (now-defunct) Windows Mobile, Windows Phone, and Windows CE/Embedded Compact.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows is the most popular desktop operating system in the world, with a 77% market share as of May 2026, and the second-most popular operating system overall, behind Android.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] As of May 2026, Windows 11 is the most used desktop version of Windows, with a market share of 72%.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] All members of the Windows product family are, as of 2026, based on Windows NT.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The first version of Windows in that product line, Windows NT 3.1, was intended for server computing and corporate workstations.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It now consists of four sub-families that tend to be released almost simultaneously and share the same kernel.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The term *Windows* collectively describes any or all of several generations of Microsoft operating system products.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The history of Windows dates back to 1981 when Microsoft started work on a program called "Interface Manager".
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The name "Windows" comes from the fact that the system was one of the first to use graphical boxes to represent programs; in the industry, at the time, these were called "windows" and the underlying software was called "windowing software".
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It was announced in November 1983 (after the Apple Lisa, but before the Macintosh) under the name "Windows", but Windows 1.0 was not released until November 1985.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 1.0 was to compete with Apple's operating system, but achieved little popularity.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 1.0 is not a complete operating system; rather, it extends MS-DOS.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The shell of Windows 1.0 is a program known as the MS-DOS Executive.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Components included Calculator, Calendar, Cardfile, Clipboard Viewer, Clock, Control Panel, Notepad, Paint, Reversi, Terminal and Write.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 1.0 does not allow overlapping windows.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Only modal dialog boxes may appear over other windows.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Microsoft sold as included Windows Development libraries with the C development environment, which included numerous windows samples.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 2.0 was released in December 1987, and was more popular than its predecessor.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It features several improvements to the user interface and memory management.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 2.03 changed the OS from tiled windows to overlapping windows.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The result of this change led to Apple Computer filing a suit against Microsoft alleging infringement on Apple's copyrights (eventually settled in court in Microsoft's favor in 1993).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 2.0 also introduced more sophisticated keyboard shortcuts and could make use of expanded memory.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 2.1 was released in two different versions: Windows/286 and Windows/386.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows/386 uses the virtual 8086 mode of the Intel 80386 to multitask several DOS programs and the paged memory model to emulate expanded memory using available extended memory.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows/286, in spite of its name, runs on both Intel 8086 and Intel 80286 processors.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It runs in real mode but can make use of the high memory area.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In addition to full Windows packages, there were runtime-only versions that shipped with early Windows software from third parties and made it possible to run their Windows software on MS-DOS and without the full Windows feature set.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The early versions of Windows are often thought of as graphical shells, mostly because they ran on top of MS-DOS and used it for file system services.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] However, even the earliest Windows versions already assumed many typical operating system functions; notably, having their own executable file format and providing their own device drivers (timer, graphics, printer, mouse, keyboard and sound).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Unlike MS-DOS, Windows allowed users to execute multiple graphical applications at the same time, through cooperative multitasking.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.0, released in 1990, improved the design, mostly because of virtual memory and loadable virtual device drivers (VxDs) that allow Windows to share arbitrary devices between multi-tasked DOS applications.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.0 applications can run in protected mode, which gives them access to several megabytes of memory without the obligation to participate in the software virtual memory scheme.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] They run inside the same address space, where the segmented memory provides a degree of protection.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.0 also featured improvements to the user interface.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Microsoft rewrote critical operations from C into assembly.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.0 was the first version of Windows to achieve broad commercial success, selling 2 million copies in the first six months.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.1, made generally available on March 1, 1992, featured a facelift.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In October 1992, Windows for Workgroups, a special version with integrated peer-to-peer networking features, was released.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Support for Windows 3.1 ended on December 31, 2001.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.2, released in 1994, is an updated version of the Chinese version of Windows 3.1.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The update was limited to this language version, as it fixed only issues related to the complex writing system of the Chinese language.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 3.2 was generally sold by computer manufacturers with a ten-disk version of MS-DOS that also had Simplified Chinese characters in basic output and some translated utilities.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The next major consumer-oriented release of Windows, Windows 95, was released on August 24, 1995.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] While still remaining MS-DOS-based, Windows 95 introduced support for native 32-bit applications, plug and play hardware, preemptive multitasking, long file names of up to 255 characters, and provided increased stability over its predecessors.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 95 also introduced a redesigned, object oriented user interface, replacing the previous Program Manager with the Start menu, taskbar, and Windows Explorer shell.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The first OSR of Windows 95 was also the first version of Windows to be bundled with Microsoft's web browser, Internet Explorer.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Mainstream support for Windows 95 ended on December 31, 2000, and extended support for Windows 95 ended on December 31, 2001.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 95 was followed up with the release of Windows 98 on June 25, 1998, which introduced the Windows Driver Model, support for USB composite devices, support for ACPI, hibernation, and support for multi-monitor configurations.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 98 also included integration with Internet Explorer 4 through Active Desktop and other aspects of the Windows Desktop Update (a series of enhancements to the Explorer shell which was also made available for Windows 95).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In June 1999, Microsoft released Windows 98 Second Edition, an updated version of Windows 98.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 98 SE added Internet Explorer 5.0 and Windows Media Player 6.2 amongst other upgrades.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Mainstream support for Windows 98 ended on June 30, 2002, and extended support for Windows 98 ended on July 11, 2006.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] On September 14, 2000, Microsoft released Windows Me (Millennium Edition), the last DOS-based version of Windows.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] However, Windows Me was faced with criticism for its speed and instability, along with hardware compatibility issues and its removal of real mode DOS support.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] *PC World* considered Windows Me to be one of the worst operating systems Microsoft had ever released, and the fourth worst tech product of all time.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In November 1988, a new development team within Microsoft (which included former Digital Equipment Corporation developers Dave Cutler and Mark Lucovsky) began work on a revamped version of IBM and Microsoft's OS/2 operating system known as "NT OS/2".
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] NT OS/2 was intended to be a secure, multi-user operating system with POSIX compatibility and a modular, portable kernel with preemptive multitasking and support for multiple processor architectures.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] However, following the successful release of Windows 3.0, the NT development team decided to rework the project to use an extended 32-bit port of the Windows API known as Win32 instead of those of OS/2.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Win32 maintained a similar structure to the Windows APIs (allowing existing Windows applications to easily be ported to the platform), but also supported the capabilities of the existing NT kernel.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Following its approval by Microsoft's staff, development continued on what was now Windows NT, the first 32-bit version of Windows.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] However, IBM objected to the changes, and ultimately continued OS/2 development on its own.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows NT was the first Windows operating system based on a hybrid kernel.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The hybrid kernel was designed as a modified microkernel, influenced by the Mach microkernel developed by Richard Rashid at Carnegie Mellon University, but without meeting all of the criteria of a pure microkernel.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The first release of the resulting operating system, Windows NT 3.1 (named to associate it with Windows 3.1) was released in July 1993, with versions for desktop workstations and servers.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows NT 3.5 was released in September 1994, focusing on performance improvements and support for Novell's NetWare, and was followed up by Windows NT 3.51 in May 1995, which included additional improvements and support for the PowerPC architecture.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows NT 4.0 was released in June 1996, introducing the redesigned interface of Windows 95 to the NT series.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] On February 17, 2000, Microsoft released Windows 2000, a successor to NT 4.0.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The Windows NT name was dropped at this point in order to put a greater focus on the Windows brand.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The next major version of Windows NT, Windows XP, was released to manufacturing (RTM) on August 24, 2001, and to the general public on October 25, 2001.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The introduction of Windows XP aimed to unify the consumer-oriented Windows 9x series with the architecture introduced by Windows NT, a change which Microsoft promised would provide better performance over its DOS-based predecessors.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] At retail, Windows XP was marketed in two main editions: the "Home" edition was targeted towards consumers, while the "Professional" edition was targeted towards business environments and power users, and included additional security and networking features.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Mainstream support for Windows XP ended on April 14, 2009.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Extended support ended on April 8, 2014.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] After Windows 2000, Microsoft also changed its release schedules for server operating systems; the server counterpart of Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, was released in April 2003.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It was followed in March 2006, by Windows Server 2003 R2.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] After a lengthy development process, Windows Vista was released only for volume licensing on November 30, 2006, and finally, on January 30, 2007, it was officially released to everyone, including consumers.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It contained a number of new features, from a redesigned shell and user interface to significant technical changes, with a particular focus on security features.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It was available in a number of different editions, and has been subject to some criticism, such as drop of performance, longer boot time, criticism of new UAC, and stricter license agreement.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Vista's server counterpart, Windows Server 2008 was released in early 2008.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] On July 22, 2009, Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 were released to manufacturing (RTM) and were officially released, including for the public, months later on October 22, 2009.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Unlike its predecessor, Windows Vista, which introduced a large number of new features, Windows 7 was intended to be a more focused, incremental upgrade to the Windows line, with the goal of being compatible with applications and hardware with which Windows Vista was already compatible.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 8, the successor to Windows 7, was released generally on October 26, 2012.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] A number of significant changes were made on Windows 8, including the introduction of a user interface based around Microsoft's Metro design language with optimizations for touch-based devices such as tablets and all-in-one PCs.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] These changes include the Start screen, which uses large tiles that are more convenient for touch interactions and allow for the display of continually updated information, and a new class of apps which are designed primarily for use on touch-based devices.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The new Windows version required a minimum resolution of 1024×768 pixels, effectively making it unfit for netbooks with 800×600-pixel screens.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] An update to Windows 8, called Windows 8.1, was released on October 17, 2013, and includes features such as new live tile sizes, deeper OneDrive integration, and many other revisions.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 8 and Windows 8.1 have been subject to some criticism, such as the removal of the Start menu.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] On September 30, 2014, Microsoft announced Windows 10 as the successor to Windows 8.1.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It was released on July 29, 2015, and addresses shortcomings in the user interface first introduced with Windows 8.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Changes on PC include the return of the Start Menu, a virtual desktop system, and the ability to run Windows Store apps within windows on the desktop rather than in full-screen mode.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 10 is said to be available to update from qualified Windows 7 with SP1, Windows 8.1 and Windows Phone 8.1 devices from the Get Windows 10 Application (for Windows 7, Windows 8.1) or Windows Update (Windows 7).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In February 2017, Microsoft announced the migration of its Windows source code repository from Perforce to Git.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] This migration involved 3.5 million separate files in a 300-gigabyte repository.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] By May 2017, 90 percent of its engineering team was using Git, in about 8500 commits and 1760 Windows builds per day.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In June 2021, shortly before Microsoft's announcement of Windows 11, Microsoft updated their lifecycle policy pages for Windows 10, revealing that support for their last release of Windows 10 will end on October 14, 2025.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] On April 27, 2023, Microsoft announced that version 22H2 would be the last of Windows 10.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] On June 24, 2021, Windows 11 was announced as the successor to Windows 10 during a livestream.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The new operating system was designed to be more user-friendly and understandable.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] As of May 2022, Windows 11 is a free upgrade to Windows 10 users who meet the system requirements.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In July 2021, Microsoft announced it will start selling subscriptions to virtualized Windows desktops as part of a new *Windows 365* service in the following month.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The new service will allow for cross-platform usage, aiming to make the operating system available for both Apple and Android users.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It is a separate service and offers several variations including Windows 365 Frontline, Windows 365 Boot, and the Windows 365 app.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The subscription service will be accessible through any operating system with a web browser.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The new service is an attempt at capitalizing on the growing trend, fostered during the COVID-19 pandemic, for businesses to adopt a hybrid remote work environment, in which "employees split their time between the office and home".
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] As the service will be accessible through web browsers, Microsoft will be able to bypass the need to publish the service through Google Play or the Apple App Store.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Microsoft announced Windows 365 availability to business and enterprise customers on August 2, 2021.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Multilingual support has been built into Windows since Windows 3.0.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The language for both the keyboard and the interface can be changed through the Region and Language Control Panel.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Third-party IMEs may also be installed if a user feels that the provided one is insufficient for their needs.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Since Windows 2000, English editions of Windows NT have East Asian IMEs (such as Microsoft Pinyin IME and Microsoft Japanese IME) bundled, but files for East Asian languages may be manually installed on Control Panel.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Interface languages for the operating system are free for download, but some languages are limited to certain editions of Windows.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] This is used for most languages in emerging markets.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Full Language Packs, which translate the complete operating system, are only available for specific editions of Windows (Ultimate and Enterprise editions of Windows Vista and 7, and all editions of Windows 8, 8.1 and RT except Single Language).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] They do not require a specific base language and are commonly used for more popular languages such as French or Chinese.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] These languages cannot be downloaded through the Download Center, but are available as optional updates through the Windows Update service (except Windows 8).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The interface language of installed applications is not affected by changes in the Windows interface language.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The availability of languages depends on the application developers themselves.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012 introduce a new Language Control Panel where both the interface and input languages can be simultaneously changed, and language packs, regardless of type, can be downloaded from a central location.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The PC Settings app in Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2 also includes a counterpart settings page for this.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Changing the interface language also changes the language of preinstalled Windows Store apps (such as Mail, Maps and News) and certain other Microsoft-developed apps (such as Remote Desktop).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The above limitations for language packs are however still in effect, except that full language packs can be installed for any edition except Single Language, which caters to emerging markets.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows NT included support for several platforms before the x86-based personal computer became dominant in the professional world.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows NT 4.0 and its predecessors supported PowerPC, DEC Alpha and MIPS R4000 (although some of the platforms implement 64-bit computing, the OS treated them as 32-bit).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows 2000 dropped support for all platforms, except the third generation x86 (known as IA-32) or newer in 32-bit mode.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The client line of the Windows NT family still ran on IA-32 up to Windows 10 (the server line of the Windows NT family still ran on IA-32 up to Windows Server 2008).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] With the introduction of the Intel Itanium architecture (IA-64), Microsoft released new versions of Windows to support it.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Itanium versions of Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 were released at the same time as their mainstream x86 counterparts.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows XP 64-Bit Edition (Version 2003), released in 2003, is the last Windows client operating system to support Itanium.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows Server line continues to support this platform until Windows Server 2012; Windows Server 2008 R2 is the last Windows operating system to support Itanium architecture.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] On April 25, 2005, Microsoft released Windows XP Professional x64 Edition and Windows Server 2003 x64 editions to support x86-64 (or simply x64), the 64-bit version of x86 architecture.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows Vista was the first client version of Windows NT to be released simultaneously in IA-32 and x64 editions.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] An edition of Windows 8 known as Windows RT was specifically created for computers with ARM architecture, and while ARM is still used for Windows smartphones with Windows 10, tablets with Windows RT will not be updated.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Starting from Windows 10 Fall Creators Update (version 1709) and later includes support for ARM-based PCs.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows CE (officially known as *Windows Embedded Compact*), is an edition of Windows that runs on minimalistic computers, like satellite navigation systems and some mobile phones.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows Embedded Compact is based on its own dedicated kernel, dubbed Windows CE kernel.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Microsoft licenses Windows CE to OEMs and device makers.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The OEMs and device makers can modify and create their own user interfaces and experiences, while Windows CE provides the technical foundation to do so.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows CE was used in the Dreamcast along with Sega's own proprietary OS for the console.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows CE was the core from which Windows Mobile was derived.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Its successor, Windows Phone 7, was based on components from both Windows CE 6.0 R3 and Windows CE 7.0.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows Phone 8 however, is based on the same NT-kernel as Windows 8.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows Embedded Compact is not to be confused with Windows XP Embedded or Windows NT 4.0 Embedded, modular editions of Windows based on Windows NT kernel.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Xbox OS is an unofficial name given to the version of Windows that runs on Xbox consoles.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] From Xbox One onwards it is an implementation with an emphasis on virtualization (using Hyper-V) as it is three operating systems running at once, consisting of the core operating system, a second implemented for games and a more Windows-like environment for applications.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Microsoft updates Xbox One's OS every month, and these updates can be downloaded from the Xbox Live service to the Xbox and subsequently installed, or by using offline recovery images downloaded via a PC.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] It was originally based on NT 6.2 (Windows 8) kernel, and the latest version runs on an NT 10.0 base.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] This system is sometimes referred to as "Windows 10 on Xbox One".
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Xbox One and Xbox Series operating systems also allow limited (due to licensing restrictions and testing resources) backward compatibility with previous generation hardware, and the Xbox 360's system is backwards compatible with the original Xbox.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Up to and including every version before Windows 2000, Microsoft used an in-house version control system named Source Library Manager (SLM).
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Shortly after Windows 2000 was released, Microsoft switched to a fork of Perforce named Source Depot.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] This system was used up until 2017 when the system could not keep up with the size of Windows.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Microsoft had begun to integrate Git into Team Foundation Server in 2013, but Windows (and Office) continued to rely on Source Depot.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The Windows code in Source Depot was divided among 65 different repositories.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In 2017 Microsoft announced that it would start using Git, an open source version control system created by Linus Torvalds, and in May 2017 they reported that the migration into a new Git repository was complete.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Each Git repository contains a complete history of all the files, which tends to be very large for Windows.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Microsoft has been working on a new project called the Virtual File System for Git (VFSForGit) to address these challenges.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In 2021 the VFS for Git was superseded by **Scalar**.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Use of Windows 10 has exceeded Windows 7 globally since early 2018.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Those statistics do not include servers (including cloud computing, where Linux has significantly more market share than Windows) as Net Applications and StatCounter use web browsing as a proxy for all use.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] While the Windows 9x series offered the option of having profiles for multiple users with separate profiles and home folders, it had no concept of access privileges, allowing any user to edit others' files.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In addition, while it ran separate 32-bit applications in separate address spaces, protecting an application's code and data from being read or written by another application, it did not protect the first megabyte of memory from userland applications for compatibility reasons.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] This area of memory contains code critical to the functioning of the operating system, and by writing into this area of memory an application can crash or freeze the operating system.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] This was a source of instability as faulty applications could accidentally write into this region, potentially corrupting important operating system memory, which usually resulted in some form of system error and halt.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows NT was far more secure, implementing access privileges and full memory protection, and, while 32-bit programs meeting the DoD's C2 security rating.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Prior to Windows Vista, the default user account created during the setup process was an administrator account; the user, and any program the user launched, had full access to the machine.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Though Windows XP did offer an option of turning administrator accounts into limited accounts, the majority of home users did not do so, partially due to the number of programs which required administrator rights to function properly.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] As a result, most home users still ran as administrator all the time.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] These architectural flaws, combined with Windows's very high popularity, made Windows a frequent target of computer worm and virus writers.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Furthermore, although Windows NT and its successors are designed for security (including on a network) and multi-user PCs, they were not initially designed with Internet security in mind as much, since, when it was first developed in the early 1990s, Internet use was less prevalent.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In a 2002 strategy memo entitled "Trustworthy computing" sent to every Microsoft employee, Bill Gates declared that security should become Microsoft's highest priority.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows Vista introduced a privilege elevation system called User Account Control.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] When logging in as a standard user, a logon session is created and a token containing only the most basic privileges is assigned.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In this way, the new logon session is incapable of making changes that would affect the entire system.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] When logging in as a user in the Administrators group, two separate tokens are assigned.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] The first token contains all privileges typically awarded to an administrator, and the second is a restricted token similar to what a standard user would receive.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] User applications, including the Windows shell, are then started with the restricted token, resulting in a reduced privilege environment even under an Administrator account.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Leaked documents from 2013 to 2016 codenamed Vault 7 detail the capabilities of the CIA to perform electronic surveillance and cyber warfare, such as the ability to compromise operating systems such as Windows.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In addition, experts reported a Microsoft security vulnerability, CVE-2019-1162, based on legacy code involving Microsoft CTF and ctfmon (ctfmon.exe), that affects all Windows versions from Windows XP to the then most recent Windows 10 versions; a patch to correct the flaw is available.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Microsoft releases security patches through its Windows Update service approximately once a month (usually the second Tuesday of the month), although critical updates are made available at shorter intervals when necessary.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Versions subsequent to Windows 2000 SP3 and Windows XP implemented automatic download and installation of updates, substantially increasing the number of users installing security updates.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows integrates the Windows Defender antivirus, which is seen as one of the best available.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Windows also implements Secure Boot, Control Flow Guard, ransomware protection, BitLocker disk encryption, a firewall, and Windows SmartScreen.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In July 2024, Microsoft signalled an intention to limit kernel access and improve overall security, following a highly publicised CrowdStrike update that caused 8.5 million Windows PCs to crash.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Part of that initiative is to rewrite parts of Windows in Rust, a memory-safe language.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] In 2025 Microsoft stopped offering support to Window 10 users, including providing security updates.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Microsoft encouraged people to upgrade to Windows 11 or if this wasn't possible, to sign-up for extended security updates.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] All Windows versions from Windows NT 3 have been based on a file system permission system referred to as AGDLP (Accounts, Global, Domain Local, Permissions) in which file permissions are applied to the file/folder in the form of a 'local group' which then has other 'global groups' as members.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] These global groups then hold other groups or users depending on different Windows versions used.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] This system varies from other vendor products such as Linux and NetWare due to the 'static' allocation of permission being applied directly to the file or folder.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] However using this process of AGLP/AGDLP/AGUDLP allows a small number of static permissions to be applied and allows for easy changes to the account groups without reapplying the file permissions on the files and folders.
[src:windows-registry/microsoft-windows] Owing to the operating system's popularity, a number of applications have been released that aim to provide compatibility with Windows applications, either as a compatibility layer for another operating system, or as a standalone system that can run software written for Windows out of the box.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The **Windows Registry** is a hierarchical database that stores low-level settings for the Microsoft Windows operating system and for applications that opt to use the registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The kernel, device drivers, services, Security Accounts Manager, and user interfaces can all use the registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The registry also allows access to counters for profiling system performance.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] In other words, the registry or Windows Registry contains information, settings, options, and other values for programs and hardware installed on all versions of Microsoft Windows operating systems.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] For example, when a program is installed, a new subkey containing settings such as a program's location, its version, and how to start the program, are all added to the Windows Registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] When introduced with Windows 3.1, the Windows Registry primarily stored configuration information for COM-based components.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows 95 and Windows NT extended its use to rationalize and centralize the information in the profusion of INI files, which held the configurations for individual programs, and were stored at various locations.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] It is not a requirement for Windows applications to use the Windows Registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] For example, .NET Framework applications use XML files for configuration, while portable applications usually keep their configuration files with their executables.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Prior to the Windows Registry, .INI files stored each program's settings as a text file or binary file, often located in a shared location that did not provide user-specific settings in a multi-user scenario.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] By contrast, the Windows Registry stores all application settings in one logical repository (but also in a number of discrete files) and in a standardized form.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] According to Microsoft, this offers several advantages over .INI files.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Since file parsing is done much more efficiently with a binary format, it may be read from or written to more quickly than a text INI file.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Furthermore, strongly typed data can be stored in the registry, as opposed to the text information stored in .INI files.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] This is a benefit when editing keys manually using regedit.exe, the built-in Windows Registry Editor.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Because user-based registry settings are loaded from a user-specific path rather than from a read-only system location, the registry allows multiple users to share the same machine, and also allows programs to work for less privileged users.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Backup and restoration is also simplified as the registry can be accessed over a network connection for remote management/support, including from scripts, using the standard set of APIs, as long as the Remote Registry service is running and firewall rules permit this.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Because the registry is a database, it offers improved system integrity with features such as atomic updates.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] If two processes attempt to update the same registry value at the same time, one process's change will precede the other's and the overall consistency of the data will be maintained.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Where changes are made to .INI files, such race conditions can result in inconsistent data that does not match either attempted update.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows Vista and later operating systems provide transactional updates to the registry by means of the Kernel Transaction Manager, extending the atomicity guarantees across multiple key or value changes with traditional commit–abort semantics.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The registry contains two basic elements: **keys** and **values**.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Registry *keys* are container objects similar to folders.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Registry *values* are non-container objects similar to files.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Keys are referenced with a syntax similar to Windows' path names, using backslashes to indicate levels of hierarchy.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Keys must have a case insensitive name without backslashes.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] For example, HKEY refers to the subkey "Windows" of the subkey "Microsoft" of the subkey "Software" of the HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE root key.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Different users, programs, services or remote systems may only see some parts of the hierarchy or distinct hierarchies from the same root keys.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Registry *values* are name/data pairs stored within keys.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Registry values are referenced separately from registry keys.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Each registry value stored in a registry key has a unique name whose letter case is not significant.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The Windows API functions that query and manipulate registry values take value names separately from the key path or handle that identifies the parent key.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Registry values may contain backslashes in their names, but doing so makes them difficult to distinguish from their key paths when using some legacy Windows Registry API functions (whose usage is deprecated in Win32).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The terminology is somewhat misleading, as each registry key is similar to an associative array, where standard terminology would refer to the name part of each registry value as a "key".
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The terms are a holdout from the 16-bit registry in Windows 3, in which registry keys could not contain arbitrary name/data pairs, but rather contained only one unnamed value (which had to be a string).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] In this sense, the Windows 3 registry was like a single associative array, in which the keys (in the sense of both 'registry key' and 'associative array key') formed a hierarchy, and the registry values were all strings.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] When the 32-bit registry was created, so was the additional capability of creating multiple named values per key, and the meanings of the names were somewhat distorted.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] For compatibility with the previous behavior, each registry key may have a "default" value, whose name is the empty string.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Each value can store arbitrary data with variable length and encoding, but which is associated with a symbolic type (defined as a numeric constant) defining how to parse this data.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The keys at the root level of the hierarchical database are generally named by their Windows API definitions, which all begin with HKEY They are frequently abbreviated to a three- or four-letter short name starting with "HK" (e.g.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] However, the converse may apply for administrator-enforced policy settings where HKLM may take precedence over HKCU.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The Windows Logo Program has specific requirements for where different types of user data may be stored, and that the concept of least privilege be followed so that administrator-level access is not required to use an application.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Abbreviated HKLM, HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE stores settings that are specific to the local computer.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The key located by HKLM is actually not stored on disk, but maintained in memory by the system kernel in order to map all the other subkeys.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Applications cannot create any additional subkeys.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] On Windows NT, this key contains four subkeys—SAM, SECURITY, SYSTEM, and SOFTWARE—that are loaded at boot time within their respective files located in the %SystemRoot%\System32\config\ folder.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] A fifth subkey, HARDWARE, is volatile and is created dynamically, and as such is not stored in a file (it exposes a view of all the currently detected Plug-and-Play devices).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] On Windows Vista and above, a sixth and seventh subkey—COMPONENTS and BCD—are mapped in memory by the kernel on-demand and loaded from %SystemRoot%\System32\config\COMPONENTS or from boot configuration data, \boot\BCD on the system partition.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Object Class IDs, tying them to the applications used to handle these items.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] keys for each user profile actively loaded on the machine, though user hives are usually only loaded for currently logged-in users.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] stores settings that are specific to the currently logged-in user.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] that corresponds to the user; the same information is accessible in both locations.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] inside their own Documents and Settings subfolder (or their own Users sub folder in Windows Vista and above).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] provides runtime information into performance data provided by either the NT kernel itself, or running system drivers, programs and services that provide performance data.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] It contains information about hardware devices, including Plug and Play and network performance statistics.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The information in this hive is also not stored on the hard drive; the Plug and Play information is gathered and configured at startup and is stored in memory.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Even though the registry presents itself as an integrated hierarchical database, branches of the registry are actually stored in a number of disk files called *hives*.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Some hives are volatile and are not stored on disk at all.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] An example of this is the hive of the branch starting at HKLM\HARDWARE.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] This hive records information about system hardware and is created each time the system boots and performs hardware detection.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Individual settings for users on a system are stored in a hive (disk file) per user.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] During user login, the system loads the user hive under HKEY_USERS and sets the HKCU symbolic reference to point to the current user.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] This allows applications to store/retrieve settings for the current user implicitly under HKCU.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Not all hives are loaded at any one time.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] At boot time, only a minimal set of hives are loaded, and after that, hives are loaded as the operating system initializes and as users log in or whenever a hive is explicitly loaded by an application.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The registry is physically stored in several files, which are generally obfuscated from the user-mode APIs used to manipulate the data inside the registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Depending upon the version of Windows, there will be different files and different locations for these files, but they are all on the local machine.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The location for system registry files in Windows NT is %SystemRoot%\System32\config\; the user-specific HKEY_CURRENT_USER user registry hive is stored in Ntuser.dat inside the user profile.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] There is one of these per user; if a user has a roaming profile, then this file will be copied to and from a server at logout and login respectively.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] A second user-specific registry file named UsrClass.dat contains COM registry entries and does not roam by default.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows NT systems store the registry in a binary file format which can be exported, loaded and unloaded by the Registry Editor in these operating systems.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows 2000 keeps an alternate copy of the registry hives (.ALT) and attempts to switch to it when corruption is detected.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 do not maintain a System.alt hive because NTLDR on those versions of Windows can process the System.log file to bring up to date a System hive that has become inconsistent during a shutdown or crash.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] In addition, the %SystemRoot%\Repair folder contains a copy of the system's registry hives that were created after installation and the first successful startup of Windows.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Each registry data file has an associated file with a ".log" extension that acts as a transaction log that is used to ensure that any interrupted updates can be completed upon next startup.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Internally, Registry files are split into 4 kB "bins" that contain collections of "cells".
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The registry files are stored in %WINDIR% under the names USER.DAT and SYSTEM.DAT with the addition of CLASSES.DAT in Windows ME.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Also, each user profile (if profiles are enabled) has its own USER.DAT file which is located in the user's profile directory in %WINDIR%\Profiles\<Username>\.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The only registry file is called REG.DAT and it is stored in%WINDIR%.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] If any of the above methods worked, the device's registry files can be found in {Phone}\EFIESP\Windows\System32\config.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The registry contains important configuration information for the operating system, for installed applications as well as individual settings for each user and application.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] A careless change to the operating system configuration in the registry could cause irreversible damage, so it is usually only installer programs which perform changes to the registry database during installation/configuration and removal.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] If a user wants to edit the registry manually, Microsoft recommends that a backup of the registry be performed before the change.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] When a program is removed from control panel, it may not be completely removed and, in case of errors or glitches caused by references to missing programs, the user might have to manually check inside directories such as program files.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] After this, the user might need to manually remove any reference to the uninstalled program in the registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] This is usually done by using RegEdit.exe.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Editing the registry is sometimes necessary when working around Windows-specific issues e.g. problems when logging onto a domain can be resolved by editing the registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows Registry can be edited manually using programs such as RegEdit.exe, although these tools do not expose some of the registry's metadata such as the last modified date.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The registry editor for the 3.1/95 series of operating systems is RegEdit.exe and for Windows NT it is RegEdt32.exe; the functionalities are merged in Windows XP.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Optional and third-party tools similar to RegEdit.exe are available for many Windows CE versions.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] .REG files (also known as Registration entries) are text-based human-readable files for exporting and importing portions of the registry using an INI-based syntax.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows 9x format .REG files can be imported by Windows 2000 and later.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] These later systems also allow exporting .REG files in Windows 9x/NT format.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] String values do not require a <Value type> (see example), but backslashes (\) need to be written as a double-backslash (\\), and quotes (") as backslash-quote (\").
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Data from .REG files can be added/merged with the registry by double-clicking these files or using the /s switch in the command line.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] REG files can also be used to remove registry data.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] To remove a key (and all subkeys, values and data), the key name must be preceded by a minus sign (-).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] To remove a value (and its data), the values to be removed must have a minus sign (-) after the equal sign ({{{1}}}).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows group policies can change registry keys for a number of machines or individual users based on policies.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] When a policy first takes effect for a machine or for an individual user of a machine, the registry settings specified as part of the policy are applied to the machine or user settings.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows will also look for updated policies and apply them periodically, typically every 90 minutes.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Through its *scope* a policy defines to which machines and users the policy is to be applied.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Whether a machine or user is within the scope of a policy or not is defined by a set of rules which can filter on the location of the machine or user account in organizational directory, specific users or machine accounts or security groups.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] More advanced rules can be set up using Windows Management Instrumentation expressions.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Such rules can filter on properties such as computer vendor name, CPU architecture, installed software, or networks connected to.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] For instance, the administrator can create a policy with one set of registry settings for machines in the accounting department and policy with another (lock-down) set of registry settings for kiosk terminals in the visitors area.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] When a machine is moved from one scope to another (e.g., changing its name or moving it to another organizational unit), the correct policy is automatically applied.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] When a policy is changed it is automatically re-applied to all machines currently in its scope.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The policy is edited through a number of administrative templates which provides a user interface for picking and changing settings.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The set of administrative templates is extensible and software packages which support such remote administration can register their own templates.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The registry can be manipulated in a number of ways from the command line.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The Reg.exe and RegIni.exe utility tools are included in Windows XP and later versions of Windows.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Alternative locations for legacy versions of Windows include the Resource Kit CDs or the original Installation CD of Windows.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The /s means the file will be *silent merged* to the registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] If the /s parameter is omitted the user will be asked to confirm the operation.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] In Windows 98, Windows 95 and at least some configurations of Windows XP the /s switch also causes RegEdit.exe to ignore the setting in the registry that allows administrators to disable it.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] When using the /s switch RegEdit.exe does not return an appropriate return code if the operation fails, unlike Reg.exe which does.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] export the specified (sub)key (which has to be enclosed in quotes if it contains spaces) only.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] exports the whole registry in V4 format to an ANSI .REG file.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] exports the specified (sub)key (which has to be enclosed in quotes if it contains spaces) only.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Other command line options include a VBScript or JScript together with CScript, WMI or WMIC.exe and Windows PowerShell.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Registry permissions can be manipulated through the command line using RegIni.exe and the {{{1}}} tool.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows PowerShell comes with a registry provider which presents the registry as a location type similar to the file system.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The same commands used to manipulate files and directories in the file system can be used to manipulate keys and values of the registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Also like the file system, PowerShell uses the concept of a *current location* which defines the context on which commands by default operate.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The Get-ChildItem (also available through the aliases ls, dir or gci) retrieves the child keys of the current location.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] By using the Set-Location (or the alias cd) command the user can change the current location to another key of the registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Commands which rename items, remove items, create new items or set content of items or properties can be used to rename keys, remove keys or entire sub-trees or change values.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Through PowerShell scripts files, an administrator can prepare scripts which, when executed, make changes to the registry.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Such scripts can be distributed to administrators who can execute them on individual machines.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The PowerShell Registry provider supports transactions, i.e. multiple changes to the registry can be bundled into a single atomic transaction.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] An atomic transaction ensures that either all of the changes are committed to the database, or if the script fails, none of the changes are committed to the database.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The registry can be edited through the APIs of the Advanced Windows 32 Base API Library (advapi32.dll).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Many programming languages offer built-in runtime library functions or classes that wrap the underlying Windows APIs and thereby enable programs to store settings in the registry (e.g.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Microsoft.Win32.Registry in VB.NET and C#, or TRegistry in Delphi and Free Pascal).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] COM-enabled applications like Visual Basic 6 can use the WSH WScript.Shell object.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Another way is to use the Windows Resource Kit Tool, Reg.exe by executing it from code, although this is considered poor programming practice.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Similarly, scripting languages such as Perl (with Win32::TieRegistry), Python (with winreg), Tcl (which comes bundled with the registry package), Windows Powershell and Windows Scripting Host also enable registry editing from scripts.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The offreg.dll file, available from the Windows Driver Kit, offers a set of APIs for the creation and manipulation of currently not loaded registry hives similar to those provided by advapi32.dll.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] It is also possible to edit the registry (hives) of an offline system from Windows PE or Linux (in the latter case using open source tools).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Prior to the introduction of registration-free COM, developers were encouraged to add initialization code to in-process and out-of-process binaries to perform the registry configuration required for that object to work.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] COM applications that break because of DLL Hell issues can commonly be repaired with RegSvr32.exe or the /RegServer switch without having to re-invoke installation programs.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows exposes APIs that allows user-mode applications to register to receive a notification event if a particular registry key is changed.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] APIs are also available to allow kernel-mode applications to filter and modify registry calls made by other applications.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows also supports remote access to the registry of another computer via the RegConnectRegistry function if the Remote Registry service is running, correctly configured and its network traffic is not firewalled.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Each key in the registry of Windows NT versions can have an associated security descriptor.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The security descriptor contains an access control list (ACL) that describes which user groups or individual users are granted or denied access permissions.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The set of registry permissions include 10 rights/permissions which can be explicitly allowed or denied to a user or a group of users.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] As with other securable objects in the operating system, individual access control entries (ACE) on the security descriptor can be explicit or inherited from a parent object.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows Resource Protection is a feature of Windows Vista and later versions of Windows that uses security to deny Administrators and the system WRITE access to some sensitive keys to protect the integrity of the system from malware and accidental modification.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Special ACEs on the security descriptor can also implement mandatory integrity control for the registry key and subkeys.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] A process running at a lower integrity level cannot write, change or delete a registry key/value, even if the account of the process has otherwise been granted access through the ACL.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] For instance, Internet Explorer running in Protected Mode can *read* medium and low integrity registry keys/values of the currently logged on user, but it can only modify low integrity keys.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Outside security, registry keys cannot be deleted or edited due to other causes.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Registry keys containing NUL characters cannot be deleted with standard registry editors and require a special utility for deletion, such as RegDelNull.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows 2000 and later versions of Windows use Group Policy to enforce registry settings through a registry-specific client extension in the Group Policy processing engine.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Policy may be applied locally to a single computer using gpedit.msc or to multiple users and computers in a domain using gpmc.msc.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] With Windows 95, Windows 98, Windows ME and Windows NT 4.0, administrators can use a special file to be merged into the registry, called a policy file (POLICY.POL).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The policy file allows administrators to prevent non-administrator users from changing registry settings like, for instance, the security level of Internet Explorer and the desktop background wallpaper.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The policy file is primarily used in a business with a large number of computers where the business needs to be protected from rogue or careless users.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The default extension for the policy file is .POL.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The policy file filters the settings it enforces by user and by group (a "group" is a defined set of users).
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] To do that the policy file merges into the registry, preventing users from circumventing it by simply changing back the settings.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The policy file is usually distributed through a LAN, but can be placed on the local computer.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The policy file is created by a free tool by Microsoft that goes by the filename poledit.exe for Windows 95/Windows 98 and with a computer management module for Windows NT.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The editor requires administrative permissions to be run on systems that uses permissions.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The editor can also directly change the current registry settings of the local computer and if the remote registry service is installed and started on another computer it can also change the registry on that computer.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The policy editor loads the settings it can change from .ADM files, of which one is included, that contains the settings the Windows shell provides.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The .ADM file is plain text and supports easy localization by allowing all the strings to be stored in one place.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Windows NT kernels support redirection of INI file-related APIs into a virtual file in a registry location such as HKEY_CURRENT_USER using a feature called "InifileMapping".
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] This functionality was introduced to allow legacy applications written for 16-bit versions of Windows to be able to run under Windows NT platforms on which the System folder is no longer considered an appropriate location for user-specific data or configuration.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Non-compliant 32-bit applications can also be redirected in this manner, even though the feature was originally intended for 16-bit applications.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Similarly, application virtualization redirects all of an application's invalid registry operations to a location such as a file.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Used together with file virtualization, this allows applications to run on a machine without being installed on it.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Low integrity processes may also use registry virtualization.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] For example, Internet Explorer 7 or 8 running in "Protected Mode" on Windows Vista and above will automatically redirect registry writes by ActiveX controls to a sandboxed location in order to frustrate some classes of security exploits.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] The Application Compatibility Toolkit provides shims that can transparently redirect HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE or HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT Registry operations to HKEY_CURRENT_USER to address "LUA" bugs that cause applications not to work for users with insufficient rights.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Critics labeled the registry in Windows 95 a single point of failure, because re-installation of the operating system was required if the registry became corrupt.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] However, Windows NT uses transaction logs to protect against corruption during updates.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Current versions of Windows use two levels of log files to ensure integrity even in the case of power failure or similar catastrophic events during database updates.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p01] Even in the case of a non-recoverable error, Windows can repair or re-initialize damaged registry entries during system boot.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p02] In Windows, use of the registry for storing program data is a matter of developer's discretion.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p02] Microsoft provides programming interfaces for storing data in XML files (via MSXML) or database files (via SQL Server Compact) which developers can use instead.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p02] Developers are also free to use non-Microsoft alternatives or develop their own proprietary data stores.
[src:windows-registry/regedit-p02] In contrast to Windows Registry's binary-based database model, some other operating systems use separate plain-text files for daemon and application configuration, but group these configurations together for ease of management.
